      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</name>
                  <date when="1829-05-08"/>May 8, 1829. </dateline>
               <salute>
                  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4">Charles</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p><!--     [NOTE TO LJ: Paused here 11/12]
               Unless you are better prepared for the<lb/>
               event than I believe you could be, you will<lb/>
               be very much shocked when I tell you that<lb/>
               my brother William is no more.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The physicians had endeavored to<lb/>
               prepare us - but still we hoped and<lb/>
               thought we had reason to hope from his<lb/>
               apparent amendment. - He suddenly<lb/>
               &amp; rapidly grew worse yesterday - dreadfully<lb/>
               weaker, and weaker - and about 4 o clock<lb/>
               this morning expired in his mothers arms<lb/>
               - [underline]his mother[/underline] I may well call her who as<lb/>
               he said &amp; felt has been the kindest of mothers<lb/>
               to him - He appeared not to suffer at the<lb/>
               last - It was happy for him that his illness<lb/>
               was so short - his release so tranquil - But for<lb/>
               us it is terrible, - awful to think that but one<lb/>
               short month since he came home to us ap-<lb/>
               parently with only a cold - &amp; now is dead<lb/>
               When "On the 7[superscript]th.[/superscript] of April [insertion]he[/insertion] came home [deletion]&amp; so[/deletion] he said<lb/>
               "to M[superscript]iss[/superscript] E. on the 7[superscript]th.[/superscript] of April - my sister Charlotte<lb/>
               "died - do not be surprised if I die on the<lb/>
               "7[superscript]th.[/superscript] of May" - He died on that day - as he foretold<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-05_page03.jpg"/>

               -Never did a purer or nobler mind live in<lb/>
               this world nor one go out of it more tranquilly<lb/>
               more resigned &amp; better prepared to die -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Honora & M[insertion]rs.[/insertion] Edgeworth are wonderfully<lb/>
               well - Lucy better - A letter from<lb/>
               dear Harriet Butler this morning continues<lb/>
               to give a good account of Sophy [unclear]Rose[/unclear] - [unclear]Barry[/unclear]<lb/>
               I know has written [insertion]of[/insertion] all at Cloonagh to you<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I enclose dear Williams will<lb/>
            -->
